  "prompt": "Who writes the best class notes in IIT, Bombay?",
  "response": "It's impossible to definitively say who writes the *best* class notes in IIT Bombay for a few key reasons:\n\n*   **Subjectivity:** \"Best\" is subjective. What constitutes the best notes depends on the individual student's learning style, the specific course material, and their note-taking preferences. Some prefer detailed, verbatim notes, while others prefer concise summaries with key concepts.\n\n*   **Course-Specific:** A person might write fantastic notes for one course but struggle in another. The nature of the subject matter significantly affects the quality and effectiveness of notes.\n\n*   **Lack of Universal Access:** There's no centralized repository where all IIT Bombay students share their notes. Notes are typically shared within smaller circles of friends or study groups.\n\n*   **Constantly Changing:** Even if someone wrote exceptional notes in a particular semester, that doesn't guarantee they'll continue to do so consistently across all courses and future semesters. Teaching styles evolve, and so do individual note-taking habits.\n\n**However, here's what I can offer:**\n\n1.  **Senior-Year students:** Asking senior students about who takes good notes is a great way to get course-specific information. They often have insights into which students are known for thoroughness and clarity in their notes.\n\n2.  **Students who are naturally good at academics:** These students tend to have a better understanding of the subject, and therefore, they are able to take and write better notes.\n\n3.  **Focus on Building Your Own System:**\n\n    *   **Attend Lectures Actively:** The best notes start with attentive listening and participation in class.\n    *   **Develop Your Style:** Experiment with different note-taking methods (Cornell, outlining, mind-mapping) to find what works for you.\n    *   **Review and Revise:** Regularly review your notes and fill in any gaps.\n    *   **Collaborate:** Discuss concepts with classmates and compare notes to identify areas you might have missed.\n    *   **Don't Rely Solely on Others:** Use others' notes as a supplement, not a replacement, for your own effort.\n\nIn conclusion, while finding perfect notes from someone else might seem appealing, it's more beneficial to develop your own effective note-taking skills.\n",
